==English==

===Etymology===
First used by {{w|Lewis Carroll}} in 1871, based on the concept of two words packed together, like a {{l|en|portmanteau|gloss=a travelling case having two halves joined by a hinge}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|linguistics}} A word which combines the meaning of two words (or, rarely, more than two words), formed by combining the words, usually, but not always, by adjoining the first part of one word and the last part of the other, the adjoining parts often having a common vowel; for example, {{m|en|smog}}, formed from {{m|en|smoke}} and {{m|en|fog}}.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1871|author=Lewis Carroll|authorlink=Lewis Carroll|passage=Well, “{{l|en|slithy}}” means “lithe and slimy”. “Lithe” is the same as “active”. You see it’s like a '''portmanteau''' – there are two meanings packed up into one word.|chapter=[[s:Through the Looking-Glass, and What Alice Found There/Chapter VI|VI. Humpty Dumpty]]|title=Through the Looking-Glass, and What Alice Found There}}
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|year=2018|author=James Lambert|title=A multitude of ‘lishes’: The nomenclature of hybridity|journal=English World-Wide|page=10|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318367113_A_multitude_of_lishes_The_nomenclature_of_hybridity
|text=One reason for the popularity of '''portmanteau words''' in naming language hybrids may be the fact that the names themselves embody a type of hybridity.}}
#: {{syn|en|amalgamation|blend|frankenword|portmanteau|portmantologism}}

